133
00:07:51,160 --> 00:07:53,300
except for this brief mention right here. Sorry.

134
00:07:53,300 --> 00:07:55,720
Kore was understandably... upset.

135
00:07:55,720 --> 00:08:01,120
Demeter was full on enraged, and threatened to make all mankind starve,

136
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:04,260
so finally Zeus had to go and ask his brother to give Kore back.

137
00:08:04,280 --> 00:08:06,800
In some versions of this myth, this was a problem for Zeus,

138
00:08:06,800 --> 00:08:11,760
because he had promised Kore to his brother as a wife without telling Demeter first.

139
00:08:11,780 --> 00:08:16,580
Hades was not a dumb guy, and before he let Kore go, he offered her a snack.

140
00:08:16,620 --> 00:08:20,000
Kore had been warned to never eat anything in the underworld,

141
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:22,520
but she must've been extremely hungry by then,

142
00:08:22,520 --> 00:08:26,680
and really, I mean, how much harm could six honey sweet pomegranate seeds really do?

143
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:28,460
Well, turns out, a lot.

144
00:08:28,460 --> 00:08:32,179
In some versions, she eats them on purpose because she actually liked her husband.

145
00:08:32,179 --> 00:08:34,019
In others, she's tricked into it.

146
00:08:34,020 --> 00:08:36,580
Either way, even six seeds matter.

147
00:08:36,659 --> 00:08:43,359
Kore has to remain in the underworld for six months out of the one month for each seed that she ate,

148
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:46,620
and will spend the other six months on Olympus with her parents.

149
00:08:46,700 --> 00:08:52,100
During the six months in Olympus, Demeter would allow the fruits and grains to flourish.

150
00:08:52,100 --> 00:08:56,960
The rest of the time, Demeter would mourn Kore, who had renamed herself Persephone,

151
00:08:56,960 --> 00:09:00,080
and the ground would freeze, and nothing would grow...

152
00:09:00,080 --> 00:09:02,880
and that is why we have winter.

153
00:09:02,900 --> 00:09:03,680
Thanks thought bubble!

154
00:09:03,680 --> 00:09:08,400
So, this is a story that is significant because of its explanatory power.

155
00:09:08,420 --> 00:09:12,780
The fancy term for this is an "etiological narrative," or origin story.

156
00:09:12,860 --> 00:09:15,500
The Persephone myth explains the seasons,

157
00:09:15,500 --> 00:09:17,860
relating the cycle of planting and harvest

158
00:09:17,860 --> 00:09:20,340
to the actions of the immortals.

159
00:09:20,340 --> 00:09:25,900
For some mythologists, like E.B. Tylor, this story is an example of myth as primitive science.

160
00:09:26,260 --> 00:09:30,560
Tylor and many other scientists drew a distinction between primitive people,

161
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:36,460
who used myths to explain the world in which they lived, and modern people, who use science for that purpose.

162
00:09:36,460 --> 00:09:39,900
For Tylor, myth and science can't really be reconciled;

163
00:09:39,900 --> 00:09:44,300
science has taken the place of myth, so we don't need myths anymore.

164
00:09:44,300 --> 00:09:49,000
This is a pretty hard core theory, and since we like to view things complexly here at Crash Course,

165
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,560
we're not gonna subscribe to it, or any theory wholeheartedly.

166
00:09:52,700 --> 00:09:55,740
But we are gonna introduce some of these theories to you,

167
00:09:55,740 --> 00:09:57,380
so that you can make up your own mind.

168
00:09:57,420 --> 00:10:00,380
Right now we're not gonna get too deep into the theory of myths--

169
00:10:00,380 --> 00:10:04,620
mythography, if you wanna thrill your friends and impress people at parties,

170
00:10:04,620 --> 00:10:07,700
because I want to tell you where the series is planning to go,

171
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:11,040
but also because there are a lot of theories to mythology,

172
00:10:11,040 --> 00:10:14,080
and I don't want to include too many of them in this introduction.

173
00:10:14,080 --> 00:10:19,580
As long time viewers know, it's easy to get lost in the weeds once we start talking about theory,

174
00:10:19,580 --> 00:10:22,280
which is part of the reason we love theory so much.

175
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:27,080
And it's one of the reasons we have eight Sanskrit deities who are guardians of the right direction.

176
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:30,300
This series isn't going to be comprehensive.

177
00:10:30,300 --> 00:10:34,680
We can't present everything there is to know about thousand year old stories

178
00:10:34,680 --> 00:10:36,620
in four hundred odd minutes of video.

179
00:10:36,620 --> 00:10:39,500
But we are gonna try to introduce you to some myths you might not know,

180
00:10:39,500 --> 00:10:42,460
from places that you might be less familiar with.

181
00:10:42,460 --> 00:10:47,340
This approach is gonna be comparative and thematic, rather than geographic.

182
00:10:47,340 --> 00:10:48,160
Here's what we're planning:

183
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:50,640
The first theme we'll be covering is the most difficult:

184
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:51,760
Creation myths.

185
00:10:52,080 --> 00:10:56,080
Most cultures have some story of how the world and the people in it came to be;

186
00:10:56,080 --> 00:10:58,760
we're gonna spend a few weeks working through them.

187
00:10:58,760 --> 00:11:03,500
Be forewarned, creation myths are often mysterious, the language can be tricky or obscure,

188
